qx|62SUM,Summary|HT|d|CS|1|CP|4|AT|^-
{    Summary    }
^-|CS||CP||fp||at|^B@2^Y@3T|FP||AT|he principal coups, so called, are as follows:|
PG| ***** 171 ***** |


CP|8|FP|2|AT|

The Bath Coup,|CP||AT| - Holding up an Ace-Jack combination on the lead of the King, hoping that the Opponent will continue the suit.|
PG| ***** 172 ***** |


CP|8|AT|

The Deschapelles Coup,|CP||AT| - Sacrificing a high card (a sure winner if held on to) in order (I) to set up an entry in Partner's hand, if possible, or (2) to knock an entry our of the Dummy, to shut out the play of a long suit.|
PG| ***** 173 ***** |


CP|8|AT|

The Simple Coup,|CP||AT| - A trump-shortening play in which the Declarer reduces his own trumps to the number held by his right-hand Opponent in order to place his own holding in tenace position over the Opponents', with the lead finally in the Dummy so that the Opponent will be forced to ruff before the Declarer. In the simple coup the trump-shortening is accomplished by the ruffing of small cards (losers) from the Dummy.|
PG| ***** 174 ***** |


CP|8|AT|

The Grand Coup,|CP||AT| - Exactly like the simple coup, except that the trump-shortening is accomplished by ruffing winners led from the Dummy.|
PG| ***** 175 ***** |


CP|8|AT|

The Vienna Coup,|CP||AT| - A play preparatory to a squeeze, explained in the Chapter on squeeze plays. |
